snippet.textDisplay: If before you were born, you were told how you would die. Yet, you would know all the lives you would touch, the joy you would bring, and the experiences you would share, would you choose this life no matter the pain you would go through? I had a college roommate who was unhappy with life. I asked him, Do you like who you are? Because if you like yourself, you must accept your past. If you don't like yourself, you still have a future to make those changes. Tomorrow can only be better if you choose to make today worth living. Each day is a new day to be better. Each day is worth an experience to share. For those who are lonely, find a coffee shop and go there every day for one hour. Don't read your phone, just drink the coffee and people watch or stare out a window. Use the time to breathe. May God provide you comfort even if you don't believe in him. May my message of including God not detract from your personal joy.

snippet.textDisplay: I have several chronic illnesses and a predisposition to cancer, but hearing Xavier's story and even just experiencing this channel with the amazing people they encounter has taught me so much about how to be aware of our mortality without fear. The part of the video where Xavier mentioned how hard it is to stay in bed all day when all you want is to see your friends, or even get the mail is so real and constantly reminds me that I am never the only person feeling this way no matter how alone I feel. I used to say "if I grow up" instead of when. People always mention how "pain is temporary" but chronic literally means permanent. Forever. I can't just "get well soon" but thanks to all of the Yes Theory guys I know what I want to do with my life, so thank you.

snippet.textDisplay:
Remarkable people and video. My condolences for family and friends who lost Xavier. My best wishes to a young married couple.
I couldn't stop my tears while watching, this video contains a very powerful message that I deeply understand.

After watching and hearing this story, and understanding how it can impact others I decided to share my story also in the hope that someone will get motivated by it.
_
I was born in 1990. My father died in 1994. My mother died in 2001. My younger brother who was born in 1991. died in 2012.
I was born with HIV that I got from mother, and mother got it from my father. My younger brother wasn't breastfed because he was in an incubator as a baby because of the hearth and spine condition that he was born with.
I was diagnosed with HIV in 1994. because when my father died they did pathology exam and concluded that he was HIV positive, he didn't know it. Back in days, HIV was something not very well known and doctors gave me 1 year to live max. They gave my mother 6 months because of HIV, and my little brother maybe 6 months because of his hearth and spine condition.
Luckily somehow his spine and hearth operations were successful and he was given a couple more years.
Meanwhile, at that time, we survived the 1st war in Yugoslavia.
I was isolated in my elementary school as the only child in the classroom it was in the year 1997. That was the first time I was given HAART (Highly active antiretroviral therapy) for HIV because my condition was even worse due to stress levels but also because it was time when we weren't under sanction so the country was able to import more medicine.
In 1999. there was a second war in Yugoslavia and we were under sanctions again, so we were unable to receive medicines. My mother's condition was getting worse after sanctions and war were gone my mother and I developed resistance to the medicine. Eventually, after a couple years of struggle, she died in 2001.
Due to stress and resistance to medicine that I had, I developed AIDS (final stage) and I wasn't given much time 3-6 months. But I made a promise to my mother when she was dying that I will take care of my little brother, and that's what kept me alive fighting.
I took care of him the best way I know at the time. I finished medical school and was hoping to be able to help with new connections. But I wasn't, he died when he was 21 years old in 2012.
After he passed away I didn't know, I wanted to kill my self. My dreams of becoming a basketball player as a child were shot down when they kicked me out of the basketball team because of my HIV status, despite the fact that before they know my status they put me in a team of 14-16 and I was only 9 at the time. Then he (my brother) passed away and all my purpose in life to take care of him also passed away with him.
I was depressed for a long time and didn't know what I will do with my life. But then one day I slap my self in front of the mirror and said to my self it wasn't all for nothing. There must be something beyond my vision at the time. So I kept fighting with discrimination of society and I realized that I only need to fight my self and my fears.
I left everything behind and moved forward to a new life.
Today I have a healthy wife and a healthy child. And I am finally happy and on my own with a new family that I created after losing one that I was born with.
_
I know there are many untold motivational stories in the world. I hope I will encourage you to share yours as well as I did, in the hope that it will be helpful to someone reading it.
_
Ps. I always remember the movie "Gladiator" and scene when Djimon Hounsou as JUBA said at the end: "Now we are free. ... I will see you again ... but not yet ... not yet." Maximus was like my brain but my inner self was like Juba.

Remarkable people and video. My condolences for family and friends who lost Xavier. My best wishes to a young married couple.
I couldn't stop my tears while watching, this video contains a very powerful message that I deeply understand.

After watching and hearing this story, and understanding how it can impact others I decided to share my story also in the hope that someone will get motivated by it.
_
I was born in 1990. My father died in 1994. My mother died in 2001. My younger brother who was born in 1991. died in 2012.
I was born with HIV that I got from mother, and mother got it from my father. My younger brother wasn't breastfed because he was in an incubator as a baby because of the hearth and spine condition that he was born with.
I was diagnosed with HIV in 1994. because when my father died they did pathology exam and concluded that he was HIV positive, he didn't know it. Back in days, HIV was something not very well known and doctors gave me 1 year to live max. They gave my mother 6 months because of HIV, and my little brother maybe 6 months because of his hearth and spine condition.
Luckily somehow his spine and hearth operations were successful and he was given a couple more years.
Meanwhile, at that time, we survived the 1st war in Yugoslavia. 
I was isolated in my elementary school as the only child in the classroom it was in the year 1997. That was the first time I was given HAART (Highly active antiretroviral therapy) for HIV because my condition was even worse due to stress levels but also because it was time when we weren't under sanction so the country was able to import more medicine.

I'm a drug addict. It's only been eight days, I think, since I last used. But eight days is 7 1/2 days longer then I'd gone, without dosing since I got hooked on it. I couldn't go more than 12 hours without using or I'd be sicker than I'd ever felt, opioid withdrawal is pure hell!
I've wanted to use the last few days, so badly. I fell off and bought some, but I was so ashamed when my gf almost walked in on my about to smoke some... That I dumped it instead. That was 2 days ago. I called my connection and ordered some, then this video came on, 13:22 into the video I call him back and cancle it. I started crying. This addiction is so bad, the worse. Ive suffered through many things in my life, this addiction is so hard to fight. Hurts as much as waking up after my birthday ended to a phone call saying my mom died. I was 22. More painful than snapping 9 bones your hand st work, needing 20 months of physical therapy....

Watching this just helped me realise so many people wish they had a life to live, but their dying from some disease... And here i am depressed and escaping with drug abuse, trying to get sober, battling addiction whilst others would give anything to have my life, to have just "life". I'm so selfish. This helped me stay clean 🙏
Thank you

snippet.textDisplay: Ive never seen your channel before and i do not know this family, i can only speak from my own experience. So i hope my comment is recieved with the love and kindess that it was intended. Thank you so much for the love, joy and understanding you showed xav, you will never know how much that meant to him and his family. Understanding coupled with compassion is the biggest of deals to someone at the premmature end of their life. Incase it needs to be said, for anyone watching who may be suffering and given entirely different circumstances may feel disheartened or defeated by this very well intentioned and wonderful video that is also ok, to give up and pass away when youre/their ready. There is no right or wrong way to grieve for the loss of your own life and what could have been or the life of a loved one. I respect greatly the fight of this man I witnessed the same fight in my mother may she RIP but i also know from that lived experience that there's a time and a place to let someone go. It is not an able bodied persons right to demand or even innocently expect someone whose experience and suffering we can not understand, to fight beyond their breaking point. Yes live as long as you can and savor every joyous moment to be made but when the time comes that its inhumane to expect someone to keep fighting, let them go, peacefully and with love. The measure of a mans endurance is his own and it is not weakness to let go it takes the greatest courge to pass on into the unknown. We should all respect that and our individual circumstances.
